    <p> In the basement there was the huge shark and turtles by which you can walk through a kind of glass tunnel in the circle. Alternatively, you could jump into the pool for a certain surcharge and feed sharks. We left it through the tunnel. That was creepy enough a few times when suddenly a 2 meter long shark is behind you and you don't know about it. Then you are startled briefly. There were also huge spiked rays and turtles that hovered past us like weightlessly or lay still on the glass tube above us. </p>
    <p> We also listened to a lecture on these giants down there. We learned that stingrays are not poisonous and attacks only fatal when the sting really went straight through the heart. Haie are not as dangerous as you may think. Nevertheless, I don't want to encounter any of these fish in the wild. From the beach I might put up with it but in no way in the water. The nurse then showed us the interesting looking eggs of the sharks. They are about twice the size of a human fist and remind you very badly of a sea grass in the form of a corkscrew. </p>
    <p> Now we had learned a lot about the underwater world of Australia and decided to eat something. After enjoying a small snack on the jetty, we decided to take the short walk over to the big beach where the group then dissolved. </p>
